`]}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.p,{children:["Now we are ready to deploy and test the contract. In the test environment this is quite straightforward as described ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://hardhat.org/hardhat-runner/docs/guides/deploying",children:"here"}),". But as you would like to deploy the contract to a real network, you need to set up a few things as described ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://hardhat.org/hardhat-runner/docs/guides/verifying",children:"here"}),". First, you need to create an account on ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://www.alchemy.com/",children:"Alchemy"})," and get an API key. Then we can once again deploy the contract to the network of my choice, which was Optimism."]}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.p,{children:["Finally, we need to verify the contract on the blockchain. This is important as it allows others to see the code and verify that it is working as expected. Here again we need to set up a few things. First, you need to create an account on ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://etherscan.io/",children:"Etherscan"})," and get an API key. Then, you need to set up the ",t.jsx(e.code,{children:"ETHERSCAN_API_KEY"})," environment variable with your API key."]}),`
`,t.jsx(e.h3,{children:"The Optimism chain"}),`
`,t.jsx(e.p,{children:"One of the crucial points for the support button was that it must not be too costly to use. On the Ethereum mainnet, I have frequently encountered gas fees of 20-50 USD. This would have been prohibitive for a simple like button."}),`
`,t.jsx(e.p,{children:'Every blockchain transaction requires computational resources that must be paid for with "gas fees." These fees represent the cost of having your transaction processed and validated by the network:'}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.ul,{children:[`
`,t.jsx(e.li,{children:"On Ethereum's mainnet, high demand for block space drives fees to levels that make micro-transactions impractical"}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.li,{children:["When gas costs ",t.jsx(e.code,{className:"language-math math-inline",children:"20-50 per transaction, sending a "}),"0.50 support donation becomes economically absurd"]}),`
`,t.jsx(e.li,{children:"Layer 2 solutions like Optimism process transactions in batches and post the cryptographic proof to Ethereum, distributing that mainnet gas cost across many transactions."}),`
`]}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.p,{children:["Therefore, I decided to investigate layer-2 alternatives, which promise much lower fees. As I investigated the major alternatives, I came across ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://www.base.org/",children:"Base"}),", ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://arbitrum.io/",children:"Arbitrum"}),", ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://www.optimism.io/",children:"Optimism"})," and ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://linea.build/",children:"Linea"}),". All of them seemed fairly mature with slightly different focuses. Base is closely aligned with Coinbase, which makes it a bit less attractive for me. Linea seemed to be still quite new and not as widely adopted. Optimism on the other hand has some nice documententation, a strong community focus and a lot of projects already running on it. So I decided to go with Optimism."]}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.p,{children:["You can see all the details for the deployed contract and activity on ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://optimistic.etherscan.io/address/0x314b07fbd33a7343479e99e6682d5ee1da7f17c1",children:"Optimism Etherscan"}),"."]}),`
`,t.jsx(e.h2,{children:"The frontend"}),`
`,t.jsxs(e.p,{children:["After I had the smart contract up and running, I needed to integrate it into the website. I decided to integrate it via ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://wagmi.sh/",children:"wagmi"}),", which is a library that makes it easy to interact with Ethereum from a react app. It provides a simple API for connecting to wallets, sending transactions, and reading data from the blockchain. It is also built around ",t.jsx(e.a,{href:"https://viem.sh/",children:"viem"}),", which is a library for interacting with Ethereum in a type-safe way. This makes it easy to work with the blockchain and ensures that the code is safe and secure."]}),`
